2. Loading Data

daily_activity <- read.csv("daily_activity.csv")
sleep_day <- read.csv("sleep_day.csv")

3. Cleaning Data

3.1 Removing Duplicates

daily_activity <- daily_activity %>% distinct()
sleep_day <- sleep_day %>% distinct()

3.2 Checking for Missing Values

sum(is.na(daily_activity)) 
## [1] 0
sum(is.na(sleep_day)) 
## [1] 0

4. Data Analysis & Visualization

4.1 Calories Burned vs. Steps

ggplot(daily_activity, aes(x=TotalSteps, y=Calories)) +
  geom_point(color="red", alpha=0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method="lm", col="blue") +
  labs(title="Calories Burned vs. Steps", x="Total Steps", y="Calories Burned") +
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

4.2 Sleep Duration by Day of the Week

sleep_day$SleepDay <- as.Date(sleep_day$SleepDay, format="%d-%m-%Y")
sleep_day$DayOfWeek <- weekdays(sleep_day$SleepDay)

ggplot(sleep_day, aes(x=DayOfWeek, y=TotalSleepHours)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill="lightblue") +
  labs(title="Sleep Duration by Day of the Week", x="Day", y="Total Sleep Hours") +
  theme_minimal()

4.3 Comparison of Activity Levels

activity_long <- daily_activity %>%
  select(VeryActiveMinutes, FairlyActiveMinutes, LightlyActiveMinutes, SedentaryMinutes) %>%
  mutate(Id = row_number()) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = -Id, names_to = "ActivityType", values_to = "Minutes")

ggplot(activity_long, aes(x = ActivityType, y = Minutes, fill = ActivityType)) +
  geom_col() + 
  labs(title = "Comparison of Activity Levels", x = "Activity Type", y = "Minutes") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

4.4 Sleep Efficiency Distribution

sleep_day$SleepEfficiency <- as.numeric(gsub("%", "", sleep_day$SleepEfficiency))

ggplot(sleep_day, aes(x=SleepEfficiency)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y=after_stat(density)), binwidth=5, fill="purple", color="black", alpha=0.6) +  
  geom_density(color="red") +  
  labs(title="Distribution of Sleep Efficiency with Density Curve",
       x="Sleep Efficiency (%)", 
       y="Density") +
  theme_minimal()

5. Conclusion

  • There is a positive correlation between the number of steps taken and calories burned, indicating that higher activity levels contribute to higher calorie expenditure.
  • Sleep duration varies by day of the week, with some days showing longer sleep hours, possibly influenced by work schedules.
  • Sedentary minutes dominate the activity data, highlighting the need for users to increase their active minutes.
  • Sleep efficiency distribution suggests that while most users have good sleep efficiency, some outliers may indicate sleep disturbances.

These insights can help users optimize their physical activity and sleep patterns for better health outcomes.
